Sure, I can help you with that! Let's create a Java class for a digital clock that displays hours, minutes, and seconds. The class will have methods to set the time, increment the time by one second, and display the current time in the "HH:MM:SS" format. We'll also make sure to handle cases where seconds or minutes exceed 59.

First, we need to define the class and its properties. We'll have three integer variables to represent hours, minutes, and seconds.

```java
public class DigitalClock {
    private int hours;
    private int minutes;
    private int seconds;

    // Constructor and methods will go here
}
```

Next, we'll create a constructor to initialize the time. It's a good practice to have a default constructor and possibly one that allows setting the initial time.

```java
public DigitalClock() {
    this.hours = 0;
    this.minutes = 0;
    this.seconds = 0;
}

public DigitalClock(int hours, int minutes, int seconds) {
    this.hours = hours;
    this.minutes = minutes;
    this.seconds = seconds;
    adjustTime(); // Ensure time is within valid ranges
}
```

We need to ensure that the time set is valid. For example, if someone sets seconds to 60, it should be adjusted to 0 and increment the minutes. Similarly for minutes. Let's create a helper method `adjustTime()` to handle this.

```java
private void adjustTime() {
    minutes += seconds / 60;
    seconds %= 60;
    hours += minutes / 60;
    minutes %= 60;
    hours %= 24;
}
```

Now, let's create a method to set the time. This method should allow updating the hours, minutes, and seconds.

```java
public void setTime(int hours, int minutes, int seconds) {
    this.hours = hours;
    this.minutes = minutes;
    this.seconds = seconds;
    adjustTime();
}
```

Next, we need a method to increment the time by one second.

```java
public void increment() {
    seconds++;
    adjustTime();
}
```

Finally, we need a method to display the current time in "HH:MM:SS" format. We'll ensure that each component is zero-padded to two digits.

```java
public String displayTime() {
    return String.format("%02d:%02d:%02d", hours, minutes, seconds);
}
```

Putting it all together, here's the complete class:

```java
public class DigitalClock {
    private int hours;
    private int minutes;
    private int seconds;

    public DigitalClock() {
        this.hours = 0;
        this.minutes = 0;
        this.seconds = 0;
    }

    public DigitalClock(int hours, int minutes, int seconds) {
        this.hours = hours;
        this.minutes = minutes;
        this.seconds = seconds;
        adjustTime();
    }

    private void adjustTime() {
        minutes += seconds / 60;
        seconds %= 60;
        hours += minutes / 60;
        minutes %= 60;
        hours %= 24;
    }

    public void setTime(int hours, int minutes, int seconds) {
        this.hours = hours;
        this.minutes = minutes;
        this.seconds = seconds;
        adjustTime();
    }

    public void increment() {
        seconds++;
        adjustTime();
    }

    public String displayTime() {
        return String.format("%02d:%02d:%02d", hours, minutes, seconds);
    }

    // Optional: main method for testing
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        DigitalClock clock = new DigitalClock(23, 59, 59);
        System.out.println(clock.displayTime()); // 23:59:59
        clock.increment();
        System.out.println(clock.displayTime()); // 00:00:00
        clock.setTime(12, 30, 45);
        System.out.println(clock.displayTime()); // 12:30:45
        clock.increment();
        System.out.println(clock.displayTime()); // 12:30:46
    }
}
```

